003":"1003","1058":"1058","1068":"1068","1023":"1023","0969":"0969","968":"0968","0937":"0937","3 de febrero de 0995":"3 February 0995","Aquitaine, Francia":"Aquitaine, France","Maillezais, Departement de la Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France":"Maillezais, Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France","Maillezais,Vendée,Pays de la Loire,Frankreich":"Maillezais, Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When duc William d'Aquitaine V was born in 0969, his father, Duque Guillermo IV de Aquitania, was 32 and his mother, Duquesa Emma de Blois, was 19. He married Agnès de Bourgogne in 1018. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 30 January 1030, in Maillezais, Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France, at the age of 61, and was buried in Maillezais, Vendée, Pays de la Loire, France."},"et":{"0969–30 January 1030":"0969–30. jaanuar 1030","0969–1030":"0969–1030","0995–1068":"0995–1068","1023–1058":"1023–1058","1025–1086":"1025–1086","0937–0995":"0937–0995","0950–1003":"0950–1003","30 January 1030":"30. jaanuar 1030","1086":"1086","27 de diciembre de 1003":"27. detsember 1003","1030":"1030","990":"0990","1018":"1018","0950":"0950","0995":"0995","1025":"1025","1003":"1003","1058":"1058","1068":"1068","10